25 April 2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429211713/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/339920.html |archive-date=29 April 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|commander1_label=\n|commander2=\n|commander2_label=\n|identification_symbol=[[File:Naval Ensign of Ukraine.svg|170px|border|Ensign of Ukrainian Navy]]\n|identification_symbol_label=Naval ensign\n|identification_symbol_2= [[File:Naval jack of Ukraine.svg|170px]]\n|identification_symbol_2_label= Naval jack\n|identification_symbol_3= [[File:Naval Jack of Ukraine (1992).svg|170px]]\n|identification_symbol_3_label= Naval jack (1992)\n|identification_symbol_4= [[File:\u041d\u0417 \u0412\u041c\u0421.svg|100px]]\n|identification_symbol_4_label= Shoulder sleeve insignia (2016)\n|anniversaries=[[Navy Day (Ukraine)|Navy Day]] (every first Sunday of July<ref name=pndfsj>{{cite news |url=http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/271853.html |title=Ukrainian Navy to celebrate its holiday on first Sunday of July \u2013 decree |newspaper=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084453/http://en.interfax.com.ua/news/general/271853.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> <small>From 1997 till 2011 August 1, from 2012 till 2015 last Sunday in July).<ref name=july>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/22498.html |title=President signs Decree On Celebration of Some Memorable Dates and Professional Holidays |website=President.gov.ua |date=30 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120122012615/http://www.president.gov.ua/en/news/22498.html |archivedate=2012-01-22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3NJt5Un2AEAC&pg=PA781&dq=Ukrainian+%22Navy+day%22&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=46oIT6PvJcKAOojRxZsB&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20%22Navy%20day%22&f=false |title=The Global Road Warrior: 100 Country Handbook for the International Business Traveler |edition=3rd |first=Joe |last=Reif |publisher=[[World Trade Press]] |location=Novato, California |date=2001 |isbn=1-885073-86-0 |pages=781 |access-date=2016-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204213432/https://books.google.com/books?id=3NJt5Un2AEAC&pg=PA781&dq=Ukrainian+%22Navy+day%22&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=46oIT6PvJcKAOojRxZsB&ved=0CEMQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20%22Navy%20day%22&f=false |archive-date=2016-02-04 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AsQzDd41doAC&pg=PA250&lpg=PA250&dq=Ukrainian+Navy++August+1,+1992&source=bl&ots=yJuER86KK2&sig=bCgBoY4nj2wTJXZMp0piUt8MwuQ&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=O68IT9fTGY3m-gaxoPXGCw&sqi=2&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20Navy%20%20August%201%2C%201992&f=false |title=Ukraine Intelligence & Security Activities and Operations Handbook |volume=1 |publisher=[[International Business Publications, USA]] |location=Washington, D.C. |date=2009 |isbn=0-7397-1661-1 |pages=250 |access-date=2016-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511133159/https://books.google.com/books?id=AsQzDd41doAC&pg=PA250&lpg=PA250&dq=Ukrainian+Navy++August+1,+1992&source=bl&ots=yJuER86KK2&sig=bCgBoY4nj2wTJXZMp0piUt8MwuQ&hl=nl&sa=X&ei=O68IT9fTGY3m-gaxoPXGCw&sqi=2&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Ukrainian%20Navy%20%20August%201%2C%201992&f=false |archive-date=2016-05-11 |url-status=live }}</ref></small>\n}}\n\nThe '''Ukrainian Naval Forces''' ({{lang-uk|\u0412\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e-\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0421\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438, \u0412\u041c\u0421\u0423, Viys\u2019kovo-Mors\u2019ki Syly Ukrayiny, VMSU}}) is the [[navy]] of [[Ukraine]] and part of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]].\n\nIt consists of five branches: surface forces, submarine forces, [[Ukrainian Naval Aviation|Navy aviation]], coastal rocket-artillery and [[Marine Corps (Ukraine)|naval infantry]].<ref name=BMC>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=structure&sub=navy |title=The Navy of the Armed Forces of Ukraine |website=mil.gov.ua |date=1996-08-17 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120805142907/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=en&part=structure&sub=navy |archivedate=August 5, 2012 }}</ref> The Navy numbers 6,500 people.<ref name=unbsa2715>{{cite news |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/ukraines-navy-barely-recovering-from-its-near-death-experience-396689.html |title=Ukraine\u2019s navy barely recovering from its near-death experience |newspaper=[[Kyiv Post]] |date=29 August 2015 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110143759/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/ukraines-navy-barely-recovering-from-its-near-death-experience-396689.html |archive-date=10 January 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2007 and prior to the [[2014 Russian annexation of Crimea]] 15,470 people served the Ukrainian Navy.<ref name=unbsa2715/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/files/white_book/white_book_uk2007.pdf |title=Ukrainian Armed Forces 2007 White Book |website=mil.gov.ua |language=Ukrainian |pages=111 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080408212532/http://www.mil.gov.ua/files/white_book/white_book_uk2007.pdf |archivedate=April 8, 2008 |access-date=April 8, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe [[headquarters]] of the Ukrainian Naval Forces was, until the [[2014 Crimean crisis]], located at [[Sevastopol]] in [[Crimea]].<ref name=\"BMC\"/> The Naval Forces of Ukraine were highly affected by the Crimea Crisis as majority of their units were stationed there. Ships that did not escape or were not deployed at the time lowered their flags and were interned. Russia began a process of returning the vessels but stopped, citing inability of Ukraine to retake possession and continued violence against Russians in the Donbass. The ships that were returned were the older models of the fleet that were deemed obsolete. For example, Russia chose not to return the [[corvette]]s {{ship|Ukrainian corvette|Ternopil|U209|2}} and {{ship|Ukrainian corvette|Lutsk|U205|2}}, both of which are some of the newest ships of the Ukrainian fleet. However, none of the Ukrainian naval units retained were absorbed into the Russian Navy.\n\nUkraine had been scheduling to rebuild its naval forces since 2005<ref>[http://zakon2.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/325-2005-%D1%80 Order of the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine (9 August 2005)]. [[Verkhovna Rada]] website.</ref><ref>[http://zakon1.rada.gov.ua/laws/show/220-2006-%D0%BF Resolution of the Cabinet of Ministers of Ukraine (1 March 2006)].[[Verkhovna Rada]] website.</ref> by building the domestic project 58250, the first Ukrainian designed and built corvette, as well as ordering four patrol boats in 2013 from Willard Marine.<ref name=gsvtg>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/project-58250.htm |title=Project 58250 Corvette / Hayduk-21/Gaiduk-21  Volodymyr Velyky [\"Vladimir the Great\"] |website=globalsecurity.org |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305082430/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/project-58250.htm |archive-date=5 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bairdmaritime.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=14929:willard-marine-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-ukraine&catid=73&Itemid=65|title=Willard Marine to supply patrol boats to Ukraine|website=bairdmaritime.com|date=4 February 2014|accessdate=14 May 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160605101259/http://www.bairdmaritime.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=14929:willard-marine-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-ukraine&catid=73&Itemid=65|archivedate=5 June 2016}}</ref> Ukraine has also restarted the production of its Gryuza River Armed Artillery Boat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.azeridefence.com/ukrainian-navy-to-receive-two-gyurza-m-boats/|publisher=Azeri Defence|title=Ukrainian Navy to receive two Gyurza-M boats|date=9 November 2015|accessdate=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305183554/http://en.azeridefence.com/ukrainian-navy-to-receive-two-gyurza-m-boats/|archive-date=5 March 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe navy operates in the [[Black Sea]] basin (including [[Sea of Azov]] and [[Danube]] Delta).<ref name=\"BMC\"/> Distant operations of the Ukrainian Navy are limited to multinational activities, such as [[Operation Active Endeavour]] and [[Operation Atalanta]] in the Mediterranean and [[Horn of Africa]]. It is unknown whether these operations are funded by Ukraine.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ukrainian Cossacks Fleet 16th-17th===\n\n[[File:Kafa. 1616..jpg|thumb|310px |left|Zaporozhian Cossacks sacked Crimean [[Feodosia|Kaffa]] and freed the slaves in 1616.]]\n\nThe Ukrainian Naval Forces trace their history to the [[Zaporizhian Sich]] Cossacks, who would frequently raid [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] settlements along the Black Sea coast. Cossacks used small ships called \"chaikas\" which were similar in design to Viking long ships. Although technologically inferior to the Turks the Cossacks had great success against their opponent. In 1614 the Cossack forces were able to raid, and destroy [[Trabzon]]. In 1615 the Cossacks were able to mount a raid on [[Istanbul]] itself, destroying several suburbs of the city. In 1616 a Cossack fleet was able to reach the [[Bosphorus]], once again raiding the surrounding countryside. A Turkish fleet sent to destroy the Cossack forces was defeated in 1617. The Cossacks once again managed to mount an attack on Istanbul in 1625, forcing the [[Sultan]] to temporarily flee the capital. The Cossacks used several strategies to attack the larger Ottoman forces, such as positioning their ships during battle in a way that sun was always at their back. The Cossack ships were small with a low profile, making them hard to hit by cannon. Cossacks were typically armed with small arm muskets, and during battle had the goal of killing the crew and boarding the ship to take it over, rather than sinking the ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/unavy/aCossack1.html |publisher=Web Cite |title=Cossack Navy 16th \u2013 17th Centuries |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5knsYNTNL?url=http://www.geocities.com/unavy/aCossack1.html |archivedate=October 26, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==NAVY period==\n\n===Ukrainian People's Republic NAVY 1917\u20131921===\n\n{{see also|Navy of the Ukrainian People's Republic}}\n[[File:\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0424\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430.jpg|thumb|\u041c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0424\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430, 1918 \u0433\u043e\u0434.|305px|left|Medal of Ukrainian fleet of April 29, 1918.]]\n[[File:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446.PNG|thumb|right|305px|Gunboat \"Donets\" of Ukrainian Naval Forces, July\u2013November 1918]]\n[[File:\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043b\u0430\u0433\u0435\u0440\u044f\u0445 \u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0423\u041d\u0420, 1920 \u0433.jpg|thumb|right|305px|Ukrainian marines in 1921]]\n[[File:Sevastopol1918e.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Ukrainian warships in the port of [[Sevastopol]], 1918]]\nDuring [[1917 Russian Revolution]], several ships of the Russian Imperial Navy's [[Black Sea Fleet]], commanded and crewed by ethnic Ukrainians, declared themselves the Navy of the newly autonomous [[Ukrainian People's Republic]]. Black Sea Fleet commander [[Mikhail Sablin]] raised the colours of the Ukrainian National Republic on 29 April 1918.<ref>[http://ukrainianweek.com/History/22688 Operation Fleet For Ukraine], [[The Ukrainian Week]] (16 May 2011)</ref><ref>{{in lang|ru}} [https://ru.krymr.com/a/interactive-map/29189950.html Crimean campaign of Peter Bolbochan in 1918], [[Radio Free Europe]] (April 2018)</ref> However, few further steps on establishing a navy were made as the Ukrainian government lost control over coastal territories.\n\nAfter the Revolution 1917, a time of anarchy and demoralization overtook the former Russian Black Sea Fleet. The Fleet, stationed in [[Sevastopol]], was commanded by a collective, \"Tsentroflot\". Different political influences clashed: Ukrainian, [[Bolshevik]], [[Menshevik]], [[Social Revolutionaries]] and [[Anarchist]]. Very different flags were hoisted over ships: Ukrainian bicolors, old Russian ensigns, Bolshevist red flags and Anarchist black flags.<ref>[http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/ua~1918.html Ukraine \u2013 Historical Naval Flags (1918)], accessed October 2009</ref> They were hoisted and lowered even several times daily, according to changes of each crew's political orientation. The Ukrainian People's Republic aspired to take control of the Fleet. On 22 December 1917 the Naval Ministry in Kiev was established.\n\nStarting October 1917 the crews of the ships established military councils; the [[Flag of Ukraine|blue-yellow flags]] were flying from the masts. The ships Zavidniy (Enviable) and [[Russian cruiser Pamiat Merkuria (1907)]] were the first examples. The General Secretariat for Naval Affairs was established within the government of the [[Central Rada]] in [[Kiev]] (in January 1918 it was reformed in a Ministry). The head of it became D. Antonovich. The Main Navy Staff was led by Captain [[Jerzy \u015awirski]]. For the educational and agitational purposes of the seamen the Central Rada seconded the commissars to [[Odessa]], [[Mykolaiv]], [[Kherson]] and Sevastopol. November 22, 1917 the whole crew of the newest and most powerful warship of the Black Sea Fleet ''Volya'' swore fealty to the Central Rada, followed soon by several ships and submarines. On 29 April 1918, Rear-admiral M. Sablin was appointed commander-in-chief of the Ukrainian Navy. A telegram to Kiev was sent from the staff ship ''Georgiy Pobedonosets'' \u201cEffective today the Sevastopol fortress and the Fleet in Sevastopol raised the Ukrainian flag. Admiral Sablin assumed the command of the Fleet\u201d. Having no reply the admiral ordered to repeat the telegram beginning with the words \u201cComrades of Kiev Central Rada...\u201d. But Sablin was unaware that at that moment the Central Rada in Kiev was already history.\n\nUkraine had a navy for five months. From October 1917 till March 1918 the following came to be at the disposal of the Ukrainians: nine [[battleships]], seven [[cruisers]], 18 [[destroyers]], 14 [[submarines]], 16 [[patrol ships]] and avisos, 11 military transports and mother ships. Additionally, the Fleet\u2019s Headquarters, all military institutions and plants, all coastal fortifications were in hands of the Ukrainians. But they were yet to face a disaster.\n\nThe Kaiser\u2019s forces had been advancing on Sevastopol with a goal to capture the Black Sea Fleet. Having no support from the land forces, Admiral Sablin was forced enter negotiations regarding cessation of hostilities. The [[History of Germany during World War I|Germans]] however rejected the armistice proposals and the advance continued.\n\nIn April 1918 German and Ukrainian troops [[Crimea Operation (1918)|invaded Crimea]]. On 29 April 1918, fleet-commanding Rear-admiral Sablin (Russian) gave an order to hoist Ukrainian national flags over all ships in Sevastopol (the medal to the right commemorates that event). But Germans started to occupy Sevastopol, because the bolsheviks began to lead away ships. Centroflot (the combined fleet revolutionary committee), in order to save the Fleet, took a decision to move it to [[Novorossiysk]]. But on April 30, 1918, only the small part of the fleet under command of Admiral Sablin, which trusted the bolsheviks, headed for Novorossiysk and hoisted Russian St. Andrew (saltire) ensigns. The greater part of the Ukrainian fleet remained in Sevastopol \u2013 there were 30 destroyers and torpedo boats, 25 auxiliaries, 7 battleships and small craft as well as 15 submarines left in Sevastopol under Admiral Myhaylo Ostrogradskiy who in this situation assumed command.\n\nOn 1 May 1918 Germans captured the ships remaining in Sevastopol, because the actions of Bolsheviks violated the peace agreement. On 17 June 1918, 1 dreadnought and 6 destroyers returned from Novorossiysk to Sevastopol, where they were also captured. The greater part of the ships remaining in Novorossiysk were destroyed by their own crews on [[Lenin]]'s command. In July\u2013November 1918 Germans gradually transferred many ships to the command of Ukrainian government ([[Hetman]] [[Pavlo Skoropadskyi]]). The main Ukrainian sea power concentrated in Odessa and Mykolaiv was more than 20 minesweepers, 7 small cruisers, 1 dreadnought and more than 30 auxiliaries. In Sevastopol there were only 2 old battleships under Ukrainian flags. On 18 July 1918 the Naval Ministry in [[Kiev]] established new naval ensigns and some rank flags (e.g. flag of Naval Minister, flag of Deputy Minister). The old Russian jack remained as Ukrainian naval jack. It was regarded as symbol of glory of Black Sea Fleet, whose crews were in large part previously Ukrainian. On 17 September Germans gives Ukraine 17 U-boats. In December 1918, when naval forces of [[Allies of World War I|the Entente]] were approaching Sevastopol, Ukrainian Rear-admiral V. Klokhkovskyy (\u0412'\u044f\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041a\u043b\u043e\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439) commanded all ships to hoist [[Order of St. Andrew|Russian St. Andrew (saltire) ensigns]]. It was a demonstration of good intentions for the Entente. However, the Entente captured the Black Sea Fleet and subsequently transferred it to the [[White movement|Russian \"White\" forces]]. In Ukrainian hands remained only small in numbers subdivisions of marines. Ukrainian naval authorities existed until 1921.\n\n====List of Ukrainian ships====\n[[File:\u041f\u0430\u043c\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043c\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0444\u043b\u0430\u0433 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b 1917.jpg|thumbnail|Blue and yellow flag on cruiser Pamiat Merkuria, Nov 1917]]\nOn October 17, 1917 the 2nd rank Captain Ye.Akimov was appointed the representative of the [[Central Council of Ukraine]] at the command of the [[Black Sea Fleet]]. In November 1917 in [[Sevastopol]] was established the Sahaidachny Sea Battalion ([[kurin]]) which on November 24, 1917 was sent to [[Kiev]] to extinguish Bolshevik uprisings and participated in the [[Kiev Arsenal January Uprising]].\n\nOn December 29, 1917 most of the [[Black Sea Fleet]] was taken over by [[Bolshevik]]s.\n\nEarlier in December 1917 the Black Seas Fleet squadron under Ukrainian flags led by the [[Russian battleship Imperator Aleksandr III]] and included another cruiser and three destroyers participated in the evacuation of the 127th Infantry Division from [[Trabzon]] back to [[Ukraine]].\n\nBaltic Fleet\n* [[Soviet cruiser Krasnyi Krym]] (October 12, 1917)\n* Russian destroyer Ukraina (October 12, 1917)\n* Russian destroyer Haidamak (October 12, 1917)\n\nBlack Sea Fleet\n* [[Russian battleship Georgii Pobedonosets]] (November 9, 1917)\n* [[Russian cruiser Pamiat Merkuria (1907)]] (November 12, 1917)\n* Russian destroyer Zorkiy (November 12, 1917)\n* Russian destroyer Zvonkiy (November 12, 1917)\n* [[Russian battleship Imperator Aleksandr III|Russian Battleship Volya (previously Imperator Aleksandr III)]] (November 22, 1917)\n* [[Russian battleship Imperatritsa Ekaterina Velikaya]]\n\n====Legacy====\nOn 29 April 2018 [[Ukrainian President]] [[Petro Poroshenko]] and [[Ukrainian Prime Minister|Prime Minister]] [[Volodymyr Groysman]] greeted Ukrainian Navy personnel on the 100th anniversary since the foundation of Ukraine's Navy.<ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/10099364-ukraine-marks-100th-anniversary-of-ukraine-s-navy.html Ukraine marks 100th anniversary of Ukraine's Navy], [[UNIAN]] (29 April 2018)</ref> The Black Sea Fleet raised the colours of the Ukrainian National Republic on 29 April 1918.\n\n===Independence 1991-period \"Battle for the oath\"===\n\nThe origins of the contemporary Ukrainian Naval Forces intertwined with the fate of the [[Soviet Black Sea Fleet]] and with the modern history of the [[Crimea]]. Following the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] (1991), the administration of the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] passed to the Joint Armed Forces of the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] for a transitional period pending agreement on the division of the ex-Soviet military between members of the [[former Soviet Union]]. [[Marshal of Aviation]] [[Yevgeny Shaposhnikov]] became commander of the Joint CIS Armed Forces command on 14 February 1992.\n\nOn 6 December 1991 the [[Supreme Council of Ukraine]] (Verkhovna Rada) adopted a resolution on the laws of Ukraine \"About the Defense of Ukraine\" and \"About the Armed Forces of Ukraine\", as well as the text of a military oath. On the same day, in the [[parliament of Ukraine]] chamber, the [[Minister of Defense of Ukraine]], [[Kostyantyn Morozov]], became the first person to take the oath. On 10 December 1991 the Supreme Council of Ukraine ratified the [[Belavezha Accords]]. On 12 December 1991 the [[President of Ukraine]] issued [[ukase]] #4, ordering all military formations based in Ukraine to pledge allegiance by 20 January 1992. The vast majority of the Black Sea Fleet ignored the order. On 1 January 1992 the newspaper ''Vympyel'' of the Black Sea Fleet [[Filipp Oktyabrskiy]] Training unit (edited by Captain-Lieutenant Mykola Huk) published the military oath and the anthem of Ukraine in the [[Ukrainian language]].\n\nOn 3 January 1992 Ukraine started the practical formation of its national armed forces. On 8 January 1992 the Officers' Assembly of the Black Sea Fleet appealed to all leaders of the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] to recognise the Black Sea Fleet as an operational-strategic formation and not subordinate to Ukraine. On 12 January 1992, the brigade of [[Soviet Border Troops|border troops]] in [[Balaklava]] ([[Sevastopol]]) became the first military formation to pledge allegiance to Ukraine. On 14 January 1992 the Governor of Sevastopol appealed to the Supreme Councils of both Ukraine and the Russian Federation, urging faster adoption of a decision on the status of the Black Sea Fleet. On 16 January 1992, an agreement between the participants of [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] was signed on the oath in strategic formations.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://zakon.nau.ua/doc/?code=997_142 |title=Text of the agreement on oath in the strategic formations |publisher=Zakon.nau.ua |date=1992-01-16 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030090703/http://zakon.nau.ua/doc/?code=997_142 |archivedate=October 30, 2014 }} \n</ref>\nOn 18 January 1992, the 3rd company of the divers school became the first formation of the Black Sea Fleet to pledge their allegiance to Ukraine, along with the Maritime Department of the Sevastopol Institute of Instrument Engineering. On the next day, forty-six naval pilots pledged their allegiance to Ukraine at the central square (''Ploshcha Lenina'') of [[Mykolaiv]].\n\nBlack Sea Fleet military personnel previously under the oath of the [[Soviet Armed Forces]] did not hasten to pledge allegiance to the newly formed state. First Deputy Commander-in-Chief of the Russian Navy [[Admiral of the Fleet (Soviet Union)|Fleet Admiral]] [[Ivan Kapitanets]] issued a directive: \"to apply severe sanctions, including dismissal from office and separation from service to officers, midshipmen, and warrant officers who create an unhealthy situation in military communities that are prone to treason and taking the oath of allegiance to Ukraine \". Nonetheless, on 26 January 1992 the 17th Brigade of Ships for the Guarding the Water Area of the Crimea Naval Base followed the example of the divers.<ref name=\"vms-hist\"/> Right before the [[Soviet Army Day|Soviet Army and Navy Day]] (23 February) on 22 February, the 880th Independent Naval Infantry Battalion of Black Sea Fleet pledged allegiance to Ukraine. The battalion had been recognized{{by whom|date=October 2014}} as the best formation of the fleet in 1991. The Main Navy Staff in Moscow issued an order to dissolve the battalion. After the incident, all military units of the [[Black Sea Fleet]] recruited exclusively Russians{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}.\n\nAccording to estimations by the [[International Institute for Strategic Studies]], in January of 1992 the Black Sea Fleet accounted for 80,000 servicemen, 69 major warships including 3 aircraft carriers, 6 missile cruisers, 29 submarines, 235 warplanes and helicopters, and great number of ships of auxiliary fleet.<ref name=forum86>[http://diasporiana.org.ua/wp-content/uploads/books/12761/file.pdf What is Black Sea Fleet Worth?]. \"Forum, a Ukrainian review\" at Diasporiana. No.86. Summer, 1992. page 35.</ref> Without informing Ukraine with which it supposed to share control over the Black Sea Fleet in a framework of the Joint Armed Forces Command, the Russian Federation was selling away several ships.<ref name=forum86/>\n\nFrom the beginning, relationships between the newly formed states of Russia Federation and the Republic of Ukraine were tense. In January 1992 the [[Supreme Soviet of Russia]] raised the question of the political status of [[Crimea]] ([[Crimean Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Crimean ASSR]]) and of the constitutionality of the 1954 decision to transfer of [[Crimean Oblast]] of the [[Russian SFSR]] to the [[Ukrainian SSR]], accusing [[Nikita Khrushchev]] of treason against the [[Russian people]]. Although never annulled,{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} many Russian parliamentarians refused to recognize the legal document, pointing out the procedural errors during its adoption. The Ukrainian side issued reminders of the number of international treaties and agreements between the two countries, such as the 19 November 1990 treaty between the Russian SFSR and the Ukrainian SSR, in which both sides recognized the territorial integrity of the other, as well as the [[Belavezha Accords]] (an agreement on creation of the Commonwealth of Independent States) of 8 December 1991 and the [[Alma-Ata Protocol]] of 21 December 1991.\n\nNoticing not much reaction from the Black Sea Fleet command located on the territory of Ukraine, on 5 April 1992 the [[President of Ukraine]] issued Decree #209 \"About urgent measures on development of the Armed Forces of Ukraine\", which accused the [[Russian Federation]] and the Joint Armed Forces command of intervening in the internal affairs of Ukraine. On 6 April 1992, a session of the 6th Congress of People's Deputies of the Russian SFSR refused to accept the Belavezha agreement as previously ratified by the Supreme Council of the Russian SFSR (on 12 December 1991). Also, on 6 April 1992, the [[President of Ukraine]] appointed [[Borys Kozhyn]] as the Commander of Ukrainian Naval Forces. The next day, the [[President of Russia]] issued a Decree \"On the transfer of the Black Sea Fleet under jurisdiction of the Russian Federation\". On 9 April 1992, the effect of both decrees were suspended until the end of the Russian-Ukrainian talks.\n\n===Ukrainian division of the Black Sea Fleet 1991\u20131997===\n\n[[File:Boat U170 Skadovsk 2012 G1.jpg|thumbnail|Ukrainian Navy artillery boat ''Zhuk'' class U170 ''Skadovs'k'' off the [[Bay of Sevastopol]], [[Crimea]]]]\n\nIn September 1991, an office of the [[:uk:\u0421\u043f\u0456\u043b\u043a\u0430 \u043e\u0444\u0456\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0456\u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|Society of Ukrainian Officers]] was opened in [[Sevastopol]] on the initiative of Major [[Volodymyr Kholodyuk]] and captains-lieutenant [[Ihor Tenyukh]] and [[Mykola Huk]].<ref name=\"vms-hist\">{{cite web |title=Ukrainian Navy History |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/vms-hist.htm |website=globalsecurity.org |date=27 March 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303200357/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/vms-hist.htm |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The society become the initiator and nucleus of the organization of the Ukrainian Naval Forces. On 7 April 1992 at 17:00 37 officers of the administration and headquarters of the Crimean Naval Base (an administrative entity and not a physical \"base\") pledged their allegiance and loyalty to people of Ukraine. Rear Admiral Borys Kozhyn, who was in charge, was not present at that time of the event. He was in the office of [[Ivan Yermakov]] accepting a proposition of the First Deputy Chairman of the Supreme Council of Ukraine to become the commander of the future Ukrainian Naval Forces. On 8 April 1992 the [[Minister of Defense of Ukraine|Minister of Defense]] signed a directive \"About creation of the Ukrainian Naval Forces\". On 13 April 1992 an organizational group was established on creation of the Ukrainian Naval Forces, which upset the command of the [[Black Sea Fleet]].\n\nThe current history of the Ukrainian Naval Forces began on 1 August 1992, when it was formally established by order of the President of Ukraine [[Leonid Kravchuk]]. This was followed by a long and controversial [[Black Sea Fleet#Partition of the Soviet Black Sea Fleet|partition of the Soviet Black Sea Fleet]] between newly independent Ukraine and the [[Russian Federation]].\n\n[[File:SKR-112-Ukraine.png|thumb|600 px|right|SKR-112 on 20 July 1992]]\nOne of the episodes of this process was the story of ''[[SKR-112]]'' \u2013 effectively the first Ukrainian Navy ship.<ref name=uknavy>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/vms.htm |title=Ukrainian Navy |website=globalsecurity.org |date=26 April 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721134518/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/ukraine/vms.htm |archive-date=21 July 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 20 July 1992, the crew of ''SKR-112'' declared itself a Ukrainian ship and raised the [[Flag of Ukraine|Ukrainian flag]]. The Navy headquarters in Moscow considered this a [[mutiny]] and attempted to act accordingly. The ship left its base on the Crimean peninsula bound for [[Odessa]], causing a chase and ramming attempts by ships still loyal to Moscow. Soon several other ships, auxiliary vessels, and coastal units of the Black Sea Fleet followed ''SKR-112''{{'}}s decision but with less violent outcomes.\n\nIt was only in 1997 that the ships and equipment of the Black Sea Fleet were officially divided between the two countries. The new Russian formation retained its historic name \"Black Sea Fleet\". Under the terms of a negotiated lease agreement it was also granted rights to use the majority of its bases on the Crimea Peninsula, Ukraine on a renewable ten-year [[lease]] basis at least until 2017. The newly established Ukrainian Naval Forces received dozens of vessels (mostly obsolete or inoperative, not unlike some of those retained by Russia) and some shore-based infrastructure. However, the Russian Navy lost several important facilities, most notably the ''NITKA'' (Russian acronym for \"Scientific testing simulator for shipborne aviation\") [[naval aviation]] training facility in [[Saky]], and the [[special forces]] base in [[Ochakiv]]. The process of fleet division remained painful since many aspects of the two navies' co-existence were under-regulated, causing recurring conflicts.\n\n[[File:\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u201c\u0421\u0456 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0437 - 2016\u201d (28075162974).jpg|right|thumb|The [[Krivak-class frigate|Krivak III-class]] frigate {{ship|Ukrainian frigate|Hetman Sahaydachniy|U130|2}} is the current flagship of the Ukrainian Navy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kozhara-hetman-sahaidachny-frigate-to-join-natos-anti-piracy-operation/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130917123531/http://www.interfax.co.uk/ukraine-news/kozhara-hetman-sahaidachny-frigate-to-join-natos-anti-piracy-operation/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 September 2013 |title=Kozhara: Hetman Sahaidachny frigate to join NATO\u2019s anti-piracy operation |newspaper=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=17 September 2013}}</ref>]]\n\nSince 1997 due to lack of financing and neglect most of the Ukrainian naval units have been scrapped or poorly maintained. By 2009, only the [[frigate]] {{ship|Ukrainian frigate|Hetman Sahaydachniy|U130|2}}, originally built to be a Soviet Border Guards ship, was capable of long endurance missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://day.kiev.ua/277204/ |title=The Destruction of a Squadron. A sequel |publisher=Day.kiev.ua |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717050438/http://www.day.kiev.ua/277204/ |archivedate=July 17, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nJoint exercises of the Ukrainian Naval Forces and the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]] resumed after a seven-year interval in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=14908782&PageNum=0 |title=Ukraine and Russia to resume joint naval exercises |newspaper=[[ITAR-TASS]] |date=12 March 2010}} {{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\nMost of the Ukrainian naval assets, as those of the other branches of the armed forces, comprise mainly [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-era equipment; no major plan for modernization has yet emerged, except for a new corvette design completed in 2009 but not built.<ref name=uknavy/>\n\nOn 19 December 2008, [[United States Ambassador to Ukraine]] [[William B. Taylor, Jr.]] stated that [[Minister of Defense of Ukraine|Ukrainian Defense Minister]] [[Yuriy Yekhanurov]] and [[US Defense Secretary]] [[Robert Gates]] were discussing the purchase by Ukraine of one to three [[U.S. Navy]] frigates.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/3523/ |title=The Washington Charter on Strategic Partnership confirms guarantees of Ukraine's security, says U.S. ambassador |newspaper=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=22 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815184924/http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/3523/ |archivedate=August 15, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009, the design for a new corvette (designed exclusively by Ukraine and to be built at Ukrainian shipyards) for the Ukrainian Naval Forces was completed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/21808/ |title=Yushchenko pressed for the development of a new Ukrainian corvette |newspaper=[[Interfax-Ukraine]] |date=12 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521002352/http://www.interfax.com.ua/eng/main/21808/ |archivedate=May 21, 2011 }}</ref> That month the [[Ministry of Defence (Ukraine)|Ukrainian defense ministry]] and Chernomorsky Shipyard ([[Mykolaiv]]) signed a contract upon results of the governmental tender for corvettes. The Shipbuilding Research and Design Center (Mykolaiv) was selected the project developer.\n\nIf built, the ship was supposed to operate in the Black and the Mediterranean seas; her endurance would be 30 days, [[Displacement (ship)|displacement]] 2,500 tons. Leading European arms manufacturers like DCNS, MBDA, and EuroTorp were to deliver weapons for the project. Commissioning of the lead ship was scheduled for 2016. It was planned to build four corvettes before 2021. According to the corvette construction program approved by Ukrainian government in March 2011, overall amount of program financing till 2021 would be about UAH 16.22 billion. Given the bankrupt state of the Ukrainian economy, as of 2016 the completion of this project is uncertain.{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n\n=== NAVY after Russian military attack in 2014 ===\n\n==== Vessels captured by the Russian navy ====\n\n24 March 2014, most of the Ukrainian ships in Sevastopol were taken by the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]],<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mail.com/int/news/europe/2726272-pro-russian-crowds-seize-3-ukrainian-warships.html#.1258-stage-hero1-2) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140321042623/http://www.mail.com/int/news/europe/2726272-pro-russian-crowds-seize-3-ukrainian-warships.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=2014-03-21 |title=Pro-Russian crowds seize 3 Ukrainian warships \u2013 Europe news |publisher=Mail.com |date=2014-03-20 |accessdate=2014-04-23 }}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://en.itar-tass.com/russia/724676|title=Over 70 military units in Crimea hoist Russian flags|newspaper=[[Russian News Agency TASS|TASS]]|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326062812/http://en.itar-tass.com/russia/724676|archive-date=26 March 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> including several aircraft and other equipment. On 8 April 2014 an agreement was reached between Russia and Ukraine to return Ukrainian Navy materials to Ukraine proper.<ref name=\"JDW12414\"/> A part of the Ukrainian Navy was then returned to Ukraine but Russia suspended this agreement because/after [[War in Donbass#Post-ceasefire government offensive|Ukraine did not renew its unilaterally declared ceasefire on 1 July 2014]] in the [[War in Donbass]].<ref name=\"korrespondent.net\"/>\n\nOn 11 January 2018 [[Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] stated that Russia was \"ready to return Ukrainian military ships that are still in Crimea, we are ready to hand over aviation equipment and armored vehicles.\"<ref name=\"auto\">[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/2341737-putin-says-russia-ready-to-return-ukrainian-military-ships-aircraft-left-in-crimea.html Putin says Russia ready to return Ukrainian military ships, aircraft left in Crimea], [[UNIAN]] (12 January 2018)</ref>\n\nList of captured ships of the [[Ukrainian Navy]].<ref>[http://intvua.com/news/85520-my-nash-my-novyy-flot-postroim-spisok-ukradennyh-korabley-vmsu.html List of stolen ships of the Ukrainian Navy]. INTV. March 21, 2014</ref> On 8 April 2014, an agreement had been reached between [[Russia]] and [[Ukraine]] to return captured vessels to Ukraine and \"for the withdrawal of an undisclosed number of Ukrainian aircraft seized in [[Crimea]]\".\n\nSee also\n*[[List of former ships of the Ukrainian Navy]]\n\n=== Modern Ukrainian NAVY from 2015 ===\n\n[[File:Naval Ensign of Ukraine.svg|thumb|right|310px|Naval ensign of Ukraine]]\n[[File:\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0431\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0412\u041c\u0421 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0456 \u0431\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438 \u0432 \u0445\u043e\u0434\u0456 \u0432\u0438\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044c \u0437\u0434\u0456\u0439\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f (27359525951).jpg|thumb|right|310px|]]\n\n\nAs of 24 March 2014, all of the larger ships but one (the frigate {{ship|Ukrainian frigate|Hetman Sahaydachniy}}) of the Ukrainian Navy were captured by the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]].<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-navy-seizes-last-ukrainian-ship-in-crimea-1395779516\n |title=One-Ship Ukraine Navy Defies Russia to the End\n |last=Shishkin\n |first=Philip\n |date=26 March 2014\n |website=www.wsj.com\n |publisher=[[The Wall Street Journal Europe]] ([[Dow Jones & Company]])\n |url-access=subscription\n |access-date=7 November 2017\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107222153/https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-navy-seizes-last-ukrainian-ship-in-crimea-1395779516\n |archive-date=7 November 2017\n |url-status=live\n }}</ref> Some ships Russia returned to Ukraine. In 2015 Ukraine received 5 small (7 and 11 meter aluminum) Willard Marine patrol boats; the original order was placed in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/willard-marine-wins-order-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-international-navies/eb8f27f84edd709d9ca807b5d874e019.html|publisher=Homeland Security Today|title=Willard Marine Wins Order To Supply Patrol Boats To International Navies|access-date=2015-06-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212230030/http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/willard-marine-wins-order-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-international-navies/eb8f27f84edd709d9ca807b5d874e019.html|archive-date=2016-02-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sprotyv.info/ru/news/kiev/na-voenno-morskoy-baze-v-odesse-osvaivayut-amerikanskie-katera-dlya-specnaza-foto|publisher=Information Resistance|title=\u041d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0432 \u041e\u0434\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0441\u0432\u0430\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0430.|access-date=2015-06-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623024019/http://sprotyv.info/ru/news/kiev/na-voenno-morskoy-baze-v-odesse-osvaivayut-amerikanskie-katera-dlya-specnaza-foto|archive-date=2015-06-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn summer of 2014 construction of Gurza-M was revived and the first two vessels were expected to be completed in fall of 2015.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150706000204/http://dumskaya.net/news/na-stolichnom-zavode-udarnymi-tempami-delayut-br-043365/ At the capital city factory in shocking pace are being built armored boats for the Odessa river division of Ukrainian Navy]. Dumskaya. 3 February 2015</ref> In December 2016 the first two Gurza-M officially joined the Ukrainian Navy.<ref name=2016YoUa /> The new military contract is for 20 vessels that should be completed by 2020.<ref name=2016YoUa />\n\n[[File:P191 Starobilsk (unloading).jpg|300px|thumb|left|Unloading of the boats in Odessa.]]\nOn September 27, 2018, the ''Drummond'' and the [[USCGC Cushing (WPB-1321)|USCGC ''Cushing'']] were formally transferred to [[Ukraine]], after their retirement.<ref name=navaltoday2018-09-27/> The two vessels were shipped, as deck cargo, and arrived in Odessa on October 21, 2019.<ref name=Usni2019-10-21/>\n\nThe Rescue ship \"\u041eleksandr Okhrimenko\" was formally disposed to the Ukrainian Navy from the Ministry of Infrastructure on August 29, 2019.\n\nThe Project 58181 Centaur (Kentavr) class is a series of small armored assault craft being built for the Ukrainian Navy. The first two vessels were laid down at the Kuznya na Rybalskomu in December 2016. The project was developed by State Research and Design Shipbuilding Center on the basis of the Gyurza-M class artillery boats. Designed for carrying patrol service on rivers and coastal maritime areas, delivery and landing of marines. 2 schip On trial, 1 in order.\n\nUkrainian shipbuilder PSC Kuznya on Rybalsky launched a new medium reconnaissance ship for the Ukrainian Navy on 23 April 2019.[2]\n\nOn 20 October 2019 an unfinished middle-sized reconnaissance ship of the Laguna project was launched in Kherson, after which it made a crossing of the Dnipro river to Odessa for completion and commissioning.[3]\n\n\n\n{{Main|List of active Ukrainian Navy ships|Ukrainian Naval Aviation}}\n\n\n\n\n====New and modernized ships from 2014 to present ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:15%;\"|Class\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Photo\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Type\n! style=\"text-align:left; width:20%;\"|Ships\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Displacement\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Shipyard\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"|Commissioned\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" |Patrol \n|-\n|'''{{sclass2-|Matka|missile boat|5}}'''\n|[[File:PASSEX training in Black Sea (May 2019).jpg|150px]] \n|ex-Missile boat\n|P153 ''Pryluky''{{efn|Ship returned to the Ukrainian Navy from Crimea on 7 May 2014.<ref>{{Citeweb|url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20140508/189669831/Russia-Returns-5-More-Navy-Ships-to-Ukraine.html|title=Russia Returns 5 More Navy Ships to Ukraine|work=en.ria.ru|date=2014-05-08|accessdate=2014-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529085510/http://en.ria.ru/russia/20140508/189669831/Russia-Returns-5-More-Navy-Ships-to-Ukraine.html|archive-date=2014-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Pryluky'' is currently redeployed in Odessa.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://navaltoday.com/2014/05/08/ukrainian-missile-cutter-pryluky-finishes-first-sailing-after-redeployment/|title=Ukrainian Missile Cutter Pryluky Finishes First Sailing after Redeployment|work=navaltoday.com|date=2014-05-08|accessdate=2014-05-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509060037/http://navaltoday.com/2014/05/08/ukrainian-missile-cutter-pryluky-finishes-first-sailing-after-redeployment/|archive-date=2014-05-09|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|257\n|{{flagicon|USSR}} [[Sredne-Nevsky Shipyard]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"|1980\n|-\n| rowspan=2|'''[[Island-class patrol boat|Island]]''' || [[File:P191 Starobilsk (unloading).jpg|150px]] || rowspan=2|Patrol boat || [[P190 Sloviansk]] <ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/en/news/2019/11/13/ukrainian-navy-has-received-island-class-patrol-boats-starobilsk%E2%80%9D-sloviansk%E2%80%9D-and-search-and-rescue-vessel-oleksandr-okhrimenko%E2%80%9D/|title=Ukrainian NAVY has received Island-class patrol boats \u201cStarobilsk\u201d, \u201cSloviansk\u201d and search and rescue vessel \u201cOleksandr Okhrimenko\u201d|website=Ministry of Defence of Ukraine}}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align: center;\"| 168 || rowspan=2|{{flagicon|US}} [[Bollinger Shipyards]] || rowspan=2 style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1988\n|-\n| [[File:P191 Starobilsk.jpg|150px]] || [[P191 Starobilsk]]\n|style=\"text-align: center;\"| 164\n|-\n| rowspan=5|'''[[Gyurza-M class artillery boats|Gurza-M]]''' || rowspan=5|[[File:UkrNavy U175 Gurza-M.jpg|150px]] || rowspan=\"5\" |Patrol boat || P174 ''Akkerman'' || rowspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align: center;\"|54 || rowspan=\"5\" |{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Kuznya na Rybalskomu]] || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2016\n|-\n| P177 ''Kremenchuk'' || rowspan=3 style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2018\n|-\n| P178 ''Lubny''\n|-\n| P179 ''Vyshhorod''  \n|-\n| P180 ''Kostopil'' {{efn|Going sea trial.}} || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2019\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background: lavender;\"| Special purpose RIB\n|-\n| \u00abWillard\u00bb || [[File:Willard Sea Force.jpg|150px]] || RIB  || Sea Force 11m || 2015-2 <br> 2010-2 <br> Total-4|| {{flagicon|USA}} || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2015<ref name=\"auto4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/06/22/7071994/|title=\u0421\u0428\u0410 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456 \u0448\u0432\u0438\u0434\u043a\u0456\u0441\u043d\u0456 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438 \u201cWillard\u201d Sea Force 730 \u0456 Sea Force 11M|website=\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430}}</ref>\n|-\n| \u00abWillard\u00bb ||[[File:\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0447\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u201c\u0421\u0456 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0437 - 2016\u201d (28574529986).jpg|150px]] || RIB  || Sea Force 7.3m || 2015-3 || {{flagicon|USA}} || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2015<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"background: lavender;\"| Command and SAR/medevac  \n|-\n| '''project 2262''' || [[File:\u041c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u043d\u0444\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0438 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0412\u041c\u0421 \u0430\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0456\u0439\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u044f\u0442\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u0434\u043d\u043e \u00ab\u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041e\u0445\u0440\u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e\u00bb.jpg|150px]] || search and rescue vessel|| [[Ukrainian salvage ship Oleksandr Okhrimenko|''Oleksandr Okhrimenko'']]<ref name=\"auto2\"/> || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 2258 || {{flagicon|SIN}} [[Keppel Fels]] || style=\"text-align: center;\"| 1987 \n|-\n|}\n\n==Battles and operations==\n\n===Anti-piracy operations in Somalia===\nA Ukrainian ship carrying military cargo was hijacked off the coast of Somalia on 23 September 2008. The ship was released on 6 February 2009. All commercial news sources reported that the vessel was released after a ransom has been paid, Ukrainian officials, however, stated that special forces eliminated the pirates and retook the ship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/feb/05/somali-pirates-free-military-ship|title=Somali pirates release Ukrainian arms ship|work=the Guardian|date=6 February 2009|last=Jones|first=Sam|last2=McGreal|first2=Chris|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030220705/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/feb/05/somali-pirates-free-military-ship|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2013 Ukraine deployed its [[flagship]], the frigate ''Hetman Sahaydachniy'', as part of NATO's [[Operation Ocean Shield]] anti-piracy mission in the [[Gulf of Aden]]. The ship was deployed for a 3-month mission and operated alongside the Norwegian frigate {{ship|HNoMS|Fridtjof Nansen|F310|6}}, the Royal Danish Naval support ship {{ship|HDMS|Esbern Snare|L17|6}}, and the US Navy's frigate {{USS|De Wert|FFG-45|6}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_103997.htm|title=NATO \u2013 News: Ukraine contributes to NATO\u2019s Ocean Shield, 10-Oct.-2013|publisher=NATO|date=10 October 2013|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030203405/http://www.nato.int/cps/en/natolive/news_103997.htm|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe Naval Forces of Ukraine once again deployed ''Hetman Sahaydachniy'' with an anti-submarine [[Ka-27]] helicopter aboard to the coast of Somalia as part of the [[European Union]]'s [[Operation Atlanta]] on 3 January 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.for-ua.com/news/2014/01/03/120845.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 18, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819085926/http://en.for-ua.com/news/2014/01/03/120845.html |archivedate=August 19, 2014 }}</ref> The ship was recalled on 3 March 2014 to Ukraine in response to the [[Crimea Crisis]].\n\n===2014 Russia attack Crimea===\nPrior to the Crimea Crisis Ukraine maintained a very modest naval force for a nation that lacked shores with any of the world's oceans. In the [[2014 Crimean crisis]], Russia annexed Crimea, where the majority of the bases of the Ukrainian Navy were located. Twelve thousand of Ukraine's 15,450 Navy personnel were based in Crimea{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}. 2 Ukrainian navy officers were killed by Russian marines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-military-idUSBREA360GB20140407|title=Russian marine kills Ukraine navy officer in Crimea, says ministry|date=April 7, 2014|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref> Russia took control of at least 12 of Ukraine's 17 ships. The naval base north of Odessa became the main operational Ukrainian Naval base. Ukraine also lost control of its Navy's main underground ammunition-storage site at the [[Inkerman]] valley, outside Sevastopol, as well as of its helicopter-repair facilities. The Navy's 750-strong 1st Naval Infantry Battalion at [[Feodosia]] was arrested and its equipment seized.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/35861/ukrainian-navy-decimated-by-russian-move-into-crimea |title=Ukrainian navy decimated by Russian move into Crimea |last=Ripley |first=Tim |date=25 March 2014 |work=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325234737/http://www.janes.com/article/35861/ukrainian-navy-decimated-by-russian-move-into-crimea |archivedate=2014-03-25 }}</ref> Ukraine temporarily lost 51 ships, mostly auxiliaries, to Russia as the majority were stationed in Crimea. Most were returned to Ukraine after a brief internment. The fleet currently has 11, mostly small, operational ships. The main fleet force consists of one frigate commissioned in 1993 and four corvettes. Russia also returned a {{sclass2-|Polnocny|landing ship}} to Ukraine restoring Ukraine's amphibious assault capabilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.canada.com/saskatoonstarphoenix/news/world/story.html?id%3Dc03d6798-e722-4ef3-913d-c3f70fd5240a |title=Archived copy |accessdate=September 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402145224/http://www2.canada.com/saskatoonstarphoenix/news/world/story.html?id=c03d6798-e722-4ef3-913d-c3f70fd5240a |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ukrainian Marine Corps|Ukrainian Naval Infantry]] were equally affected by the crisis as Russian forces besieged the marines within their bases. Russia eventually confiscated all military equipment of the naval infantry stationed in Crimea. This was also the fate of [[Ukrainian Naval Aviation]] as all their assets on the peninsula were confiscated as well, several planes and helicopters did manage to make their way to mainland Ukraine prior to Russia fully taking over the region. The 10th Saki Naval Aviation Brigade, controlling all the Ukrainian Navy's air units, managed to get a number of its aircraft airborne to bases in mainland Ukraine on 5 March 2014.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Ripley |title=Ukrainian Navy decimated by Russian move into Crimea |work=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |date=2 April 2014 |pages=17}}</ref> However, more than a dozen aircraft and helicopters undergoing maintenance had to be abandoned.\n\nOn 8 April 2014 an agreement was reached between Russia and Ukraine to return interned vessels to Ukraine and \"for the withdrawal of an undisclosed number of Ukrainian aircraft seized in Crimea\".<ref name=JDW12414>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/36695/russia-begins-returning-ukraine-naval-vessels-and-aircraft |title=Russia begins returning Ukraine naval vessels and aircraft |work=[[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |date=12 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418042848/http://www.janes.com/article/36695/russia-begins-returning-ukraine-naval-vessels-and-aircraft |archivedate=April 18, 2014 }}</ref> At the time Russian Navy sources claimed the Ukrainian ships were \"not operational because they are old, obsolete, and in poor condition\".<ref name=JDW12414/> Russia returned 35 ships but unilaterally suspended the return of Ukrainian Navy materials from [[Crimea]] to Ukraine proper because/after [[War in Donbass#Post-ceasefire government offensive|Ukraine did not renew its unilaterally declared ceasefire on 1 July 2014]] in the [[War in Donbass]].<ref name=\"korrespondent.net\">{{cite web |url=http://korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3401903-korrespondent-na-malenkom-flotu-na-chto-seichas-sposobny-ostatky-ukraynskoho-flota |script-title=ru:\u0424\u043b\u043e\u0442 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b 2014 \u2013 \u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0441\u0435\u0439\u0447\u0430\u0441 \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0431\u043d\u044b \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430 |work=Korrespondent.net |last=Seleznev |first=Denis |language=Russian |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=30 October 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141022072617/http://korrespondent.net/ukraine/politics/3401903-korrespondent-na-malenkom-flotu-na-chto-seichas-sposobny-ostatky-ukraynskoho-flota |archive-date=22 October 2014 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=ukfeb18>{{cite web |url=http://rus.newsru.ua/ukraine/18feb2016/tytan_2.html |script-title=ru:\u041c\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0451\u0442 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0443\u0434\u043d\u043e, \u0437\u0430\u0445\u0432\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u0430\u043d\u043d\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c\u0430 |language=Russian |website=news.ru.ua |date=18 February 2016 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722064224/http://rus.newsru.ua/ukraine/18feb2016/tytan_2.html |archive-date=22 July 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> 16 minor auxiliary ships are hence yet to return to Ukraine proper.<ref name=ukfeb18/>\n\nThe remaining Ukrainian naval forces continued to patrol the nation's border after being forced out of Crimea. The majority of the forces regrouped in [[Odessa]] with the coast guard having relocated its relatively small forces to [[Mariupol]] on the [[Azov Sea]] as well. The frigate ''Hetman Sahaydachniy'', recalled from a deployment along the Somalian coast was forced to deploy from its port in Odessa and intercept Russian naval vessels crossing into Ukraine's waters on 14 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charter97.org/en/news/2014/3/20/91258/|title=Frigate Hetman Sahaydachniy forces Russian ships to leave Ukrainian waters|publisher=Charter'97|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030203226/http://www.charter97.org/en/news/2014/3/20/91258/|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Defections to Russia====\nWhen Crimea was annexed by Russia, a number of Ukrainian Navy servicemen left the service for Russia. Among those were members of the upper echelon of command of the Ukrainian Navy. The Ukrainian Navy compiled and released a list of the officers who left the Ukrainian Navy for Russia, calling their actions treasonous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vmsu.org/zradniki/komanduvannya-vms-zs-ukraini/ |title=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0412\u041c\u0421 \u0417\u0421 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 / \u0414\u0435\u0437\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0440\u0438 \u0442\u0430 \u0437\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438 |publisher=vmsu.org |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804125959/http://vmsu.org/zradniki/komanduvannya-vms-zs-ukraini/ |archivedate=August 4, 2015 |url-status=unfit }}</ref>\n\n* Vice Admiral [[Sergei Yeliseyev (admiral)|Sergei Yeliseyev]], a first deputy commander.\n* Rear Admiral [[Dmitriy Shakuro]], a first deputy commander and chief of staff for the Ukrainian Navy.\n* Rear Admiral [[Denis Berezovsky]], commander-in-chief of the Ukrainian Navy for one day, now a Black Sea Fleet deputy commander and chief of the combat training directorate.\n* Colonel [[Sergei Tarkhov]], a chief of staff assistant in organization and sustainment of international relations.\n* Michman [[Sergei Gorbachov]], a sergeant major of the Ukrainian Navy.\n* Administrative command \u2013 5 officers.\n* Operation command \u2013 17 officers.\n* Intelligence command \u2013 8 officers.\n* Finance \u2013 6 officers.\n\n===Ukrainian-Russia War===\nFollowing the political coup in Kyiv and the annexation of Crimea, Russian military personnel emerged in Donetsk and Luhask oblasts demanding independence from the rest of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/04/07/pro-russian-separatists-demand-independence-from-ukraine/|title=Pro-Russian separatists demand independence from Ukraine|date=7 April 2014|work=New York Post|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103043152/http://nypost.com/2014/04/07/pro-russian-separatists-demand-independence-from-ukraine/|archive-date=3 November 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some coast guard forces that were stationed in Crimea relocated to [[Mariupol]] where they resumed patrolling the national border.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist/RTV/2014/03/26/RTV260314030/|title=UKRAINE:  Ukrainian coast guards ready to resume regular patrols along the sea border with Russia, after leaving the Crimean port of Kerch and relocating to Mariupol|publisher=ITN Source|date=26 March 2014|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030201858/http://www.itnsource.com/en/shotlist/RTV/2014/03/26/RTV260314030/|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Separatists have been active in the [[Sea of Azov]], which caused incidents with the coast guard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capital.ua/ru/news/24158-neizvestnye-voennye-atakovali-poberezhe-azovskogo-morya|script-title=ru:\u041d\u0435\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0430\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u044c\u0435 \u0410\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f|work=\u0414\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u00ab\u041a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043b\u00bb. \u0411\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0441 \u041a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430|date=5 July 2014|language=Russian|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030224325/http://www.capital.ua/ru/news/24158-neizvestnye-voennye-atakovali-poberezhe-azovskogo-morya|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSpecial Purpose units of the navy are reported to have taken part to combat the separatists. On 18 August 2014 Alex Zinchenko of the 73<sup>rd</sup> Naval Center of Special Operations was the first member of the Ukrainian Navy killed during the [[War in Donbass]] while conducting an operation near Donetsk.<ref name=\"\u0422\u0421\u041d.ua\">{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ua/ukrayina/pid-doneckom-geroyichno-zaginuv-komandir-ochakivskih-morskih-pihotinciv-363596.html|script-title=uk:\u041f\u0456\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u044c\u043a\u043e\u043c \u0433\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0457\u0447\u043d\u043e \u0437\u0430\u0433\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0438\u0440 \u043e\u0447\u0430\u043a\u0456\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0456\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0456\u0432|website=\u0422\u0421\u041d.ua|language=Ukrainian|accessdate=30 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911160930/http://tsn.ua/ukrayina/pid-doneckom-geroyichno-zaginuv-komandir-ochakivskih-morskih-pihotinciv-363596.html|archive-date=11 September 2014|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Black sea incidents===\n{{see also|List of Black Sea incidents involving Russia and Ukraine}}\n[[File:Berdyansk damaged gunboat.jpg|thumb|upright|Captured BK-02 ''Berdyansk'' with a hole in the pilothouse]]\nOn January 27, 2017, the Ukrainian diving support vessel Pochaiv was hit by sniper fire from the Tavrida drilling platform, operated by Chernomorneftegaz, being seized by Russian forces in 2014. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://censor.net.ua/en/photo_news/425240/russian_snipers_attack_ukraines_pochaiv_ship_from_seized_chornomornaftohaz_rig_ukrainian_naval_forces|title=Russian snipers attack Ukraine\u2019s Pochaiv ship from seized Chornomornaftohaz rig, \u2013 Ukrainian Naval Forces. PHOTOS|website=Censor.NET}}</ref>\n\nOn February 1, 2017, a Ukrainian Navy An-26 transport aircraft came under small arms fire from Russian military personnel, stationed on a drill rig, while flying over the Odesa gas field in the Black Sea. This gas field is located within Ukraine\u2019s exclusive economic zone, not off the Crimean peninsula, which is also part of Ukraine\u2019s EEZ. While the rig in question has not been named, it was amongst those captured by Russian forces in the aftermath of the annexation of Crimea. According to the Ukrainian military, the plane was on a training flight and was hit by small caliber shells.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rwradvisory.com/russian-military-forces-fire-on-ukrainian-vessel-and-aircraft-within-ukraines-exclusive-economic-zone-in-the-black-sea/|title=Russian Military Forces Fire on Ukrainian Vessel and Aircraft Within Ukraine\u2019s Exclusive Economic Zone in the Black Sea|date=February 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 November 2018 three Ukrainian navy vessels who attempted to redeploy from the [[Black Sea]] port [[Odessa]] to the [[Sea of Azov]] port [[Berdyansk]] were damaged and captured by the Russian [[Federal Security Service|FSB security service]] during the [[Kerch Strait incident]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-russia/russia-blocks-ukrainian-navy-from-entering-sea-of-azov-idUSKCN1NU0DL|title=Russia seizes Ukrainian ships near annexed Crimea after firing on them|first1=Andrew|last1=Osborn|first2=Pavel|last2=Polityuk|agency=Reuters|date=25 November 2018|accessdate=26 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126005901/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-russia/russia-blocks-ukrainian-navy-from-entering-sea-of-azov-idUSKCN1NU0DL|archive-date=26 November 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>[https://www.unian.info/m/politics/10351089-russia-s-don-coast-guard-ship-rams-ukrainian-tugboat-amid-transfer-from-odesa-to-mariupol-video.html Russia's 'Don' coast guard ship rams Ukrainian tugboat amid transfer from Odesa to Mariupol (video)], [[UNIAN]] (25 November 2018)</ref>\n\nDuring the summer of 2019, Russia issued a number of temporary closures, potentially interrupting navigation and nearly blocking international shipping to and from Georgia, Bulgaria, Romania and Ukraine. Since July 24, the Russia closures \u2013 announced for varying dates and timeframes \u2013 covered a total of off 120 thousand square kilometers\u2014nearly 25 percent of the entire Black Sea surface.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mil.in.ua/uk/rosiya-perekryla-chvert-chornogo-morya/|title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0447\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044c \u0427\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f|date=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the August 2019, Ukrainian Navy small reconnaissance ship Pereyaslav during their trip to Georgia to participate in exercise Agile Spirit 2019 and while in neutral waters, crew received a warning over the radio from a Russian navy ship. The Russians warned that the Ukrainians needed to turn away because the area was allegedly blocked. International coordinators did not confirm that fact, so the captain of the Pereyaslav decided to maintain the vessel along its original course. Soon thereafter, the Kasimov, a large Russian anti-submarine corvette, Project 1124M/Grisha V-class, was spotted near the Ukrainian ship. The Russian corvette\u2019s aggressive behavior only ceased when a Turkish reconnaissance plane arrived close to the Pereyaslav. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamestown.org/program/russias-black-sea-dominance-strategy-a-blend-of-military-and-civilian-assets/|title=Russia\u2019s Black Sea Dominance Strategy\u2014A Blend of Military and Civilian Assets|website=Jamestown}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 November 2019, during the Third International Conference for Maritime Security, in Odesa, Ukrainian Navy commander Admiral Ihor Voronchenko said that a Russian Tu-22M3 had been observed simulating the launch of a missile strike on this coastal city, Voronchenko added that Russian bombers had made several similar attempts during exercises on July 10, conducting a virtual airstrike 60 kilometers from Odesa.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\n==Current role==\n[[File:\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0431\u0443\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0412\u041c\u0421 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0456 \u0431\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044c\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0456 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438 \u0432 \u0445\u043e\u0434\u0456 \u0432\u0438\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044c \u0437\u0434\u0456\u0439\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f (27359525951).jpg|thumbnail|Ukrainian Navy [[Gyurza-M class artillery boats|Gurza-M class boat]], [[Odessa]]]]\nThe Naval Forces of the [[Military of Ukraine|Armed Forces of Ukraine]] are tasked with the defense of the sovereignty and state interests of [[Ukraine]] at sea. They are required to neutralize enemy naval groups in their operational zone both alone and with other branches of the Ukrainian Armed Forces, and to provide assistance from the sea to the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Ground Forces]] during their operations. Main tasks of the Navy of the Ukrainian Armed Forces are the:<ref name=\"BMC\"/>\n\n* creation and maintenance of combat forces on a level sufficient to deter maritime aggression;\n* neutralization of enemy naval forces;\n* destruction of enemy transportation;\n* support of the landing of amphibious forces and fight against enemy amphibious forces;\n* maintenance of a beneficial operational regime in the operational zone;\n* defense of its bases, sea lines of communications;\n* protection of submarine space within the territorial sea;\n* protection of the merchant fleet, maritime oil and gas industry, and other state maritime activity;\n* assistance to the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Army]] in their conduct of operations (military actions) along maritime axes;\n* participation in peacekeeping operations.\n\n===List of Commanders===\n[[File:\u0428\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0442 \u041a\u0412\u041c\u0421 \u0417\u0421\u0423.png|thumb|Standard of the Commander-in-Chief]]\n* [[Borys Kozhyn|Borys Borysovych Kozhyn]] (1992\u20131993)\n* [[Volodymyr Bezkorovainy|Volodymyr Herasymovych Bezkorovayny]] (1993\u20131996)\n* [[Mykhailo Yezhel|Mykhaylo Bronislavovych Yezhel]] (1996\u20132003)\n* Ihor Volodymyrovych Knyaz (2003\u20132006)\n* [[Ihor Tenyukh|Ihor Yosypovych Tenyukh]] (2006\u20132010)\n* Viktor Volodymyrovych Maksymov (2010\u20132012)\n* [[Yuriy Ilyin|Yuriy Ivanovych Ilyin]] (2012\u20132014)<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NVgkvXKS?url=http://president.gov.ua/documents/16469.html |archivedate=19 February 2014 |script-title=uk:\u0423\u041a\u0410\u0417 \u041f\u0420\u0415\u0417\u0418\u0414\u0415\u041d\u0422\u0410 \u0423\u041a\u0420\u0410\u0407\u041d\u0418 \u2116 84/2014 |url=http://www.president.gov.ua/documents/16469.html |language=Ukrainian |website=president.gov.ua |accessdate=14 May 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Denis Berezovsky|Denys Valentynovych Berezovsky]] (2014)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=32760 |title=\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440-\u0410\u0434\u043c\u0456\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u043e \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043c \u0412\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e-\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0417\u0431\u0440\u043e\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 |website=mil.gov.ua |date=2006-04-05 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140301190445/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=32760 |archivedate=March 1, 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[Serhiy Hayduk|Serhiy Anatoliyovych Hayduk]] (2014\u20132016)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=32771 |title=Rear Admiral D.V.Berezovsky was dismissed from duty as commander of the Naval Forces of Ukraine |publisher=Ministry of Defense of Ukraine |date=2 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140303004438/http://www.mil.gov.ua/index.php?lang=ua&part=news&sub=read&id=32771 |archivedate=March 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n* [[Ihor Voronchenko|Ihor Oleksandrovych Voronchenko]] (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2016/07/3/7113564/ |title=Poroshenko appointed the Naval Commander (\u041f\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0438\u0432 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0447\u0430 \u0412\u041c\u0421) |publisher=[[Ukrayinska Pravda]] |date=3 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703175619/http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2016/07/3/7113564/ |archivedate=3 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\n===Ranks and insignia===\n{{Main|Naval ranks and insignia of Ukraine}}\n{{see also|Admiral (Ukraine)}}\n\n===Structure===\n[[File:Ukrainian Navy - Structure 2017.png|thumb|right|560px|Structure of the Ukrainian Navy (incl. major surface combatants) in 2017]]\n* '''Ukrainian Naval Forces Command''', [[Odessa]]\n** '''[[Western Naval Base (Ukraine)|Western Naval Base]]''', [[Odessa]]\n*** 1st Surface Ships Brigade\n**** [[Ukrainian frigate Hetman Sahaydachniy (U130)|Frigate \"Hetman Sahaydachniy\" (U130)]]\n**** Missile boat \"[[Pryluky]]\" (U153)\n**** Artillery boat \"[[Berdiansk]]\" (U174)\n**** Artillery boat \"[[Akkerman]]\" (U175)\n*** 1st Security & Logistic Division\n**** Cutter \"[[Hola Prystan]]\" (U241)\n**** Training vessel \"[[Chyhyryn]]\" (U540)\n**** Training vessel \"[[Smila]]\" (U541)\n**** Training vessel \"[[Nova Kakhovka]]\" (U542)\n**** Diving vessel \"[[Pochaiv]]\" (U701)\n**** Diving cutter \"[[Volodymyr-Volynskyi]]\" (U721)\n**** Diving cutter \"RVK-268\" (U724)\n**** Water tanker \"[[Sudak]]\" (U756)\n**** Tanker \"[[Fastiv]]\" (U760)\n**** Passenger boat \"[[Illichivsk]]\" (U783)\n**** [[Degaussing]] vessel \"[[Balta, Odessa Oblast|Balta]]\" (U811)\n**** Seagoing tug \"[[Kovel]]\" (U831)\n**** Passenger boat \"[[Korosten]]\" (U853)\n**** Cutter \"RK-1942\" (U932)\n**** Tug \"BUK-239\" (U941)\n**** Tug \"[[Krasnoperekopsk]]\" (U947)\n**** 24th River Boat Division\n***** Patrol boat \"[[Skadovsk]]\" (U170)\n***** Armed cutter \"Pivdennyi\" (U171)\n***** Armed cutter \"[[Rivne]]\" (U172)\n***** Armed cutter \"AK-02\" (U173)\n*** 28th Emergency Rescue Division\n**** Fire boat \"[[Borshchiv]]\" (U722)\n**** Diving cutter \"[[Romny]]\" (U732)\n**** Diving cutter \"[[Tokmak, Ukraine|Tokmak]]\" (U733)\n**** Medical evacuation cutter \"[[Sokal]]\" (U782)\n**** [[Anchor handling tug supply vessel|Anchor handling tug]] \"[[Shostka]]\" (U852)\n** '''[[Southern Naval Base (Ukraine)|Southern Naval Base]]''', [[Mykolaiv]]\n*** 5th Surface Ships Brigade\n**** [[Ukrainian corvette Vinnytsia|Corvette \"Vinnytsia\" (U206)]]\n**** Minesweeper \"[[Henichesk]]\" (U360)\n**** Landing ship \"Yuri Olefirenko\" (U401)\n**** Landing barge \"[[Svatove]]\" (U763)\n**** [[Ukrainian ship Pereyaslav|Reconnaissance ship \"Pereiaslav\"]] (U512)\n**** Armed cutter \"AK-03\" (U938)\n*** 8th Security & Logistic Division\n**** Diving vessel \"[[Netishyn]]\" (U700)\n**** Fire boat \"[[Evpatoria]]\" (U728)\n**** Freighter \"[[Horlivka]]\" (U753)\n**** Seagoing tug \"[[Korets]]\" (U830)\n**** Diving cutter \"[[Dobropillia]]\" (U854)\n**** Towing tug \"[[Novoozerne]]\" (U942)\n** '''[[10th Naval Aviation Brigade (Ukraine)|10th Naval Aviation Brigade]]''', Mykolaiv\n** '''[[Ukrainian Naval Infantry|Fleet Marine Division]]''', Mykolaiv\n** '''406th Coastal Artillery Brigade''', Mykolaiv\n*** Headquarters & Headquarters Battery\n*** Howitzer Artillery Battalion, [[Bilhorod-Dnistrovskyi]]\n*** Howitzer Artillery Battalion, [[Berdiansk]]\n*** Howitzer Artillery Battalion, [[Sarata]]\n*** Howitzer Artillery Battalion, Dachne, Odessa Oblast\n*** Anti-tank Artillery Battalion ([[MT-12 Rapira]])\n*** Artillery Reconnaissance Battalion\n*** Security Company\n*** Engineer Company\n*** Maintenance Company\n*** Logistic Company\n*** Signal Platoon\n*** [[CBRN defense|CBRN-defense]] Platoon\n** 32nd Marine Rocket Artillery Regiment, Altestove, Odessa Oblast\n*** Headquarters & Headquarters Battery\n*** Rocket Artillery Battalion ([[BM-27 Uragan]])\n*** Rocket Artillery Battalion ([[BM-21 Grad]])\n*** Rocket Artillery Battalion ([[BM-21 Grad]])\n*** Security Company\n*** Engineer Company\n*** Maintenance Company\n*** Logistic Company\n*** Signal Platoon\n*** [[CBRN defense|CBRN-defense]] Platoon\n** 37th Signal Regiment, Radisne, Odessa Oblast\n** 801st Combat Divers Detachment, Odessa\n** 29th Coastal Reconnaissance Point, Mykolaiv\n** 84th Mine and Torpedo Arsenal, [[Ochakiv]]\n** Operational Combat Support Center, Odessa\n** [[National University - Odessa National Maritime Academy|Odessa National Maritime Academy \u2013 Ukrainian Naval College of Odessa]]\n** 198th Navy Training Center, Mykolaiv\n** 203rd Navy NCO Training School Command, Mykolaiv\n\n==Future==\nThe navy has been highly affected after Crimea returned to the Russian Federation as the majority of Ukraine's ships were stationed in Crimea. Ukraine had developed plans to rebuild their naval capability even before the crisis by planning to build 4\u201310 new corvettes at the [[Mykolaiv]] Shipyard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://survincity.com/2009/09/and-what-will-happen-to-the-project-58250-corvette/ |title=And what will happen to the Project 58250 corvette, or Ourselves s vusami |accessdate=30 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030205912/http://survincity.com/2009/09/and-what-will-happen-to-the-project-58250-corvette/ |archivedate=October 30, 2014 }}</ref> This was one of the Soviet Union's largest shipyards and it built Russia and China's only operational aircraft carriers. After the referendum in Crimea, Ukraine refused to import arms from Russia for its newly developing ships, thus it is unclear whether weapons for [[project 58250]] as Ukraine dubbed it, will be built internally in Ukraine or imported from another country.<ref name=gsvtg/>\n\nUkraine placed an order for five US-made patrol boats in October 2013, prior to the Ukrainian crisis. In February it was announced that Willard Marine won the contract to supply four boats of the {{convert|11|m|ft|adj=on|sp=us}} and {{convert|7|m|ft|adj=on|sp=us}} class with an option for a fifth. It was revealed these are the same models sold to the armed forces of Lebanon and Iraq. On 18 September 2014 it was announced that the United States and Ukraine plan further purchases of patrol boats.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/willard-marine-wins-order-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-international-navies/eb8f27f84edd709d9ca807b5d874e019.html|title=Willard Marine Wins Order To Supply Patrol Boats To International Navies|publisher=Homeland Security Today|date=10 October 2013|accessdate=14 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212230030/http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/willard-marine-wins-order-to-supply-patrol-boats-to-international-navies/eb8f27f84edd709d9ca807b5d874e019.html|archive-date=12 February 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 the United States offered Ukraine some of its {{sclass-|Oliver Hazard Perry|frigate|2}}s from its reserve fleet. The details of this offer were being worked out as of October 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.unian.info/politics/10303743-u-s-eyes-giving-ukraine-oliver-hazard-perry-frigates-to-boost-defenses-in-black-azov-seas.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-10-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018214041/https://www.unian.info/politics/10303743-u-s-eyes-giving-ukraine-oliver-hazard-perry-frigates-to-boost-defenses-in-black-azov-seas.html |archive-date=2018-10-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Units and aircraft==\n{{Main|List of active Ukrainian Navy ships|Ukrainian Naval Aviation}}\n\n[[File:Ships of Ukrainian Navy in Sevastopol, 2007.jpg|thumb|right|''Left to right'', U402 ''Konstantyn Olshansky'', U401 ''Kirovohrad'', U154 ''Kahovka'', [[Ukrainian corvette Ternopil (U209)|U209 ''Ternopil'']], and U153 ''Pryluky'']]\n\nAccording to former Navy Commander Vice Admiral [[Yuriy Ilyin]], at the beginning of 2013, the fleet had 11 warships fully ready to perform complex tasks and ten aircraft and 31 auxiliary vessels fit for service.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/commander-ukrainian-navy-to-have-11-ships-10-aircraft-31-vessels-by-end-of-2012-316992.html |title=Commander:Ukrainian Navy to have 11 ships, 10 aircraft, 31 vessels by end of 2012 |newspaper=[[Kyiv Post]] |date=30 November 2012 |accessdate=14 May 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110143759/http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/commander-ukrainian-navy-to-have-11-ships-10-aircraft-31-vessels-by-end-of-2012-316992.html |archive-date=10 January 2016 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 24 March 2014, most of the Ukrainian ships in Sevastopol were taken by the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]],<ref name=\"auto5\"/><ref name=\"auto1\"/> including several aircraft and other equipment. On 8 April 2014 an agreement was reached between Russia and Ukraine to return Ukrainian Navy materials to Ukraine proper.<ref name=\"JDW12414\"/> A part of the Ukrainian Navy was then returned to Ukraine but Russia suspended this agreement because/after [[War in Donbass#Post-ceasefire government offensive|Ukraine did not renew its unilaterally declared ceasefire on 1 July 2014]] in the [[War in Donbass]].<ref name=\"korrespondent.net\"/>\n\nOn 11 January 2018 [[Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] stated that Russia was \"ready to return Ukrainian military ships that are still in Crimea, we are ready to hand over aviation equipment and armored vehicles.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Naval Infantry===\n[[File:\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0456\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 2018 \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438.jpg|thumb|right|Ukrainian marines berets]]\nThe [[Ukrainian Naval Infantry]] (Ukrainian: \u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u0456\u0445\u043e\u0442\u0430 literally means \"Naval Infantry\") is a part of coastal guard of the Ukrainian Navy. It is used as a component part of amphibious, airborne and amphibious-airborne operations, alone or in conjunction with formations and units of the Army in order to capture parts of the seashore, islands, ports, fleet bases, coast airfields and other coast objects of the enemy. It can also be used to defend naval bases, vital areas of the shore, separate islands and coastal facilities and provide security in hostile areas.\n\nBased in [[Mykolaiv]] it is organized into a full division with 2 brigades (2 more are being activated and 1 transferred from the Ground Forces), 1 coastal and field artillery brigade and 1 multiple rocket launcher artillery regiment.\n\n==Bases==\nThe headquarters and Main Naval Base of the Ukrainian Navy were located in [[Sevastopol]] in [[Striletska Bay]] within the [[Bay of Sevastopol]].<ref name=\"BMC\"/> This is also the main base of the [[Black Sea Fleet]] of the [[Russian Navy]].  Since February\u2013March 2014 Ukrainian Naval Forces are headquartered in Odessa and based in ports in mainland Ukraine.\n\n===Other naval bases===\n* [[Western Naval Base (Ukraine)|Western Naval Base]] in [[Odessa]]<ref name=\"BMC\"/>\n* [[Southern Naval Base (Mykolaiv)|Southern Naval Base]] in [[Mykolaiv]]<ref name=\"BMC\"/> (mooring place in [[Ochakiv]])\n* [[Azov naval base (Ukraine)|Azov Naval Base]], in [[Berdyansk]] (mooring places in [[Henichesk]] and [[Mariupol]], late September 2018 two Ukrainian vessels departed from Odessa, passed the [[Crimean Bridge]] and arrived Mariupol.)<ref>[https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-defense/2551703-dmytro-kovalenko-commander-of-the-ukrainian-navy-move-to-azov-sea.html Dmytro Kovalenko, commander of the Ukrainian Navy move to Azov Sea] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031005314/https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-defense/2551703-dmytro-kovalenko-commander-of-the-ukrainian-navy-move-to-azov-sea.html |date=2018-10-31 }}, [[Ukrinform]] (4 October 2018)</ref>\n* [[Southern Naval Base (Ukraine)|Southern Naval Base]] in [[Crimea]] at: [[Novoozerne]], [[Yevpatoria]] in [[Donuzlav Lake]]<ref name=\"BMC\"/>) (lost)\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links and further reading==\n{{commons category|Ukrainian Navy}}\n*[[Jane's Navy International]], Interview: Admiral Viktor Maksymov, C.-in-C., Ukraine Navy, JNI December 2010, 34.\n* [http://rusnavy.com/history/interesting/ukranianfleet.htm?print=Y Ukrainian Navy: ferial excursions into the past and present]\n* [https://archive.is/20130419061023/http://sevsou.io.ua/s385221/boris_kojin_vice-admiral_pershiy_komanduvach_vms_ukraeni_bilya_vitokiv_vidrodjennya_viyskovo-morskih_sil_ukraeni Interview of Borys Kozhyn]. Magazine \"Hetman\". #1 (24) 2009.\n